  <h1>A country, read like a company that answers to its owners</h1>
  <SectionContext>
    The accounting identity FAND uses, the scales it operates at, and the
    vocabulary it introduces.
  </SectionContext>

  <p>
    Companies answer to their owners with a balance sheet &mdash; what they
    own, what they owe, what's left over. FAND does the same for a country.
    The twist is <em>who the owners are</em>: not shareholders, but the
    governed.
  </p>

  <h2>Read it like a 10-K</h2>
  <p>
    FAND is built as three nested layers, the way a corporate 10-K is:
    <strong>the balance sheet</strong> (one page, one bottom line &mdash;
    Net Worth), <strong>the items</strong> (produced assets, natural
    capital, human resources, substantive rights), and
    <strong>the transactions</strong> (the flows that changed those items
    over time). The goal, in John's phrase, is
    <strong>"minimizing how many <em>Whys</em> get to <em>Oh</em>"</strong>
    &mdash; a reader should be able to keep asking why a number is what it
    is, and keep getting an answer, until the <em>why</em> resolves to an
    <em>oh &mdash; I see</em>. Nothing bottoms out in "trust us."
  </p>

  <h2>A photograph and a video</h2>
  <p>
    The split between items and transactions has a simple test &mdash; the
    <strong>photograph test</strong>. A <strong>stock</strong> is something
    you could photograph at an instant: a building, a forest, a bank
    balance, a population count. A <strong>flow</strong> is an activity that
    only makes sense over a span of time: production, spending, income. A
    few stocks &mdash; Human Resources chief among them &mdash; can't
    literally be photographed but still have to be modeled; FAND calls
    these <strong>avatars</strong>, and flags them as such, so a reader
    always knows which numbers are observed and which are inferred.
  </p>

  <h2>A communication system, not a report</h2>
  <p>
    A corporate report is one-way: management reports to the owners. FAND
    is not a report &mdash; it is a <strong>communication system
    between</strong> them, with the roles the American founders assigned:
    <strong>management is government; the owners are the governed</strong>.
    That is why the balance sheet at the top of the site is not a verdict
    handed down &mdash; it is built to become a rollup of what the owners
    value, all the way down.
  </p>

  <h2>Recognize before you value</h2>
  <p>
    FAND performs two operations on anything people care about, and keeps
    them strictly separate. <strong>Recognize</strong> &mdash; acknowledge
    that something exists and matters enough that someone has spent effort
    measuring or arguing about it; recognition is deliberately generous.
    <strong>Value</strong> &mdash; assign it a worth; valuation is
    contested by nature, and those disagreements are themselves
    information. Conventional statistics collapse these two steps, quietly
    letting the measurement decide the values. FAND refuses the collapse: a
    thing recognized but not yet priced is <em>recognized and awaiting
    judgment</em> &mdash; not worth zero.
  </p>

  <h2 id="identity">The identity, worked</h2>
  <p>
    Every entity on the site &mdash; world, country, state, county, block
    group &mdash; resolves the <em>same</em> identity. Here it is, worked on
    the anchor exhibit: the United States, per person, 2025.
  </p>
  <pre>CW = PA + NC + HR + SR &minus; DM        Commonwealth &mdash; the productive base
NW = CW + CBA &minus; CBL                Net Worth &mdash; adds cross-border claim-rights, nets duties</pre>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Produced Assets (PA)</strong> &mdash; $244,619 &mdash; roads, plant, housing, machines, the built economy</li>
    <li><strong>Natural Capital (NC)</strong> &mdash; $14,258 &mdash; severable claim-rights: fuels, minerals, timber, farmland</li>
    <li><strong>Human Resources (HR)</strong> &mdash; $410,547 &mdash; the capitalized productive value of people</li>
    <li><strong>Substantive Rights (SR)</strong> &mdash; $750,927 &mdash; the "free" trust infrastructure, the largest single line</li>
    <li><strong>Cross-border claim-rights (CBA)</strong> &mdash; $62,768 &mdash; foreign assets residents hold</li>
    <li><em>(less)</em> cross-border duties + upkeep (CBL) &mdash; &minus;$89,174</li>
    <li><strong>Net Worth (NW) &mdash; $1,384,850</strong> &mdash; the bottom line</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    The biggest number on the American balance sheet is not the built
    economy, and not even its people's earning power &mdash; it is
    <strong>Substantive Rights</strong>, the trust infrastructure
    conventional accounts book at zero. The framework is built the way it
    is precisely so that this line has somewhere to live.
  </p>

  <h2>Why GDP can't see the biggest number</h2>
  <p>
    In 1913 Wesley Hohfeld showed that every legal relationship is one of
    eight positions in four correlative pairs &mdash; Right/Duty,
    Liberty/No-right, Power/Liability, Immunity/Disability. The System of
    National Accounts recognizes only the first pair. Everything else a
    society holds &mdash; the liberty to use one's own time, the power to
    participate in governance, the immunity from arbitrary interference
    &mdash; falls outside the accounting boundary and is therefore,
    silently, valued at nothing. FAND's entire analytical frontier is
    exactly the material the SNA leaves out.
  </p>

